WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.780
 So welcome back.

00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:04.060
 Now we're gonna talk about some, making our stuff look a little prettier with

00:00:04.060 --> 00:00:06.920
 imagers and how we can play with images, colors, and fonts.

00:00:06.920 --> 00:00:11.240
 So CSS and images are a lot of fun.

00:00:11.240 --> 00:00:13.020
 We can fool around with them.

00:00:13.020 --> 00:00:14.200
 We can move them around.

00:00:14.200 --> 00:00:17.720
 Actually, this for me years ago was the thing that,

00:00:17.720 --> 00:00:22.360
 in 1994, that made me fall in love with the World Wide Web.

00:00:22.360 --> 00:00:25.280
 So what made me fall in love with the World Wide Web was the ability to take a

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:29.240
 picture of me, and I love pictures of me, and then float it to the right, and

00:00:29.240 --> 00:00:30.760
 then I put a little border around here.

00:00:30.760 --> 00:00:32.240
 And so that's what I've done with CSS.

00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:35.320
 So let's take a look at how I've done that.

00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:41.120
 So if you look in line here, the navigation, which I'll show you in when I

00:00:41.120 --> 00:00:43.800
 go through the code walk, through how the navigation works.

00:00:43.800 --> 00:00:47.120
 But at this point, the end of the navigation is right here.

00:00:47.120 --> 00:00:48.360
 And I put this image in.

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:51.080
 So if you were to watch this in line, the image is right there.

00:00:51.080 --> 00:00:54.840
 But what I do is, when I say float, that actually, and

00:00:54.840 --> 00:00:57.760
 there's other things that we'll see when we start looking at fixed and

00:00:57.760 --> 00:01:01.200
 absolute positions, you can pull it out of the regular stream.

00:01:01.200 --> 00:01:03.320
 And so this is like pulled out of here.

00:01:03.320 --> 00:01:04.760
 It's as if it didn't exist.

00:01:04.760 --> 00:01:09.760
 And it floats to the right, but then it's vertically aligned.

00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:14.160
 So the next thing you see is this header one, this header one CSS.

00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:16.840
 I mean, there's a typo there, I gotta fix that.

00:01:16.840 --> 00:01:20.240
 So I'll pretend that that was an h1 there, but that's okay.

00:01:20.240 --> 00:01:24.560
 So this header, that quirks mode, I should have run this all through

00:01:26.280 --> 00:01:28.440
 the validator to make sure I'm okay.

00:01:28.440 --> 00:01:33.760
 But okay, so the top box of this CSS and images h1 is right here.

00:01:33.760 --> 00:01:36.840
 And then this floats over, but then it top aligns.

00:01:36.840 --> 00:01:40.320
 Now you can change this alignment if you like, but it top aligns here.

00:01:40.320 --> 00:01:44.200
 And then it actually looks at the width, in this case, the width of the picture.

00:01:44.200 --> 00:01:47.320
 But you can also control the width up here in the CSS.

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:49.800
 And then it carves out this space.

00:01:49.800 --> 00:01:51.960
 And then I do a margin of 1m.

00:01:51.960 --> 00:02:01.440
 And so on m, so you sort of sometimes wish they would put default formatting on.

00:02:01.440 --> 00:02:04.960
 But then they kind of tend not to put default formatting on.

00:02:04.960 --> 00:02:07.320
 Because if they did, then you have to turn that off.

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:11.200
 And so I wanted some white space, and so I had to put some white space around it.

00:02:11.200 --> 00:02:13.280
 And so I said, I'd like a margin of 1m.

00:02:13.280 --> 00:02:18.520
 And so that puts a little bit of space here, and here, and actually here as well.

00:02:18.520 --> 00:02:21.060
 So you see that this lines up over there.

00:02:21.060 --> 00:02:23.940
 And then that talks about what is a 1m.

00:02:23.940 --> 00:02:30.120
 So 1m, I could have said 5 pixels, 5px, and that would have been fine.

00:02:30.120 --> 00:02:34.520
 But 1m is basically the width of the letter m, roughly.

00:02:34.520 --> 00:02:40.240
 It's sort of, it is a width that changes with the size and nature of the font.

00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:44.320
 I think of it as the width of an m, and I think that might be a soft definition of

00:02:44.320 --> 00:02:46.120
 it, but I don't think it's a precise definition of it.

00:02:46.120 --> 00:02:48.360
 But that's what I did.

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:53.480
 So float right, hoist it, and sends it over here, and then shoves this over.

00:02:53.480 --> 00:02:59.720
 So that this text is now, it reserves this space, the text is wrapped, basically.

00:02:59.720 --> 00:03:04.080
 And then I held out some space just for prettiness, right?

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:06.680
 And so that's like CSS is making it look pretty.

00:03:06.680 --> 00:03:12.120
 Now, what happens here is, sometimes you wanna basically force,

00:03:12.120 --> 00:03:15.960
 after this float has happened, something back to the left margin.

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:19.820
 And there's this clear equals all that says clear any floats,

00:03:19.820 --> 00:03:21.400
 is what it's really saying.

00:03:21.400 --> 00:03:26.440
 And so it means that even though this, if it wasn't for clear equals all,

00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:29.400
 this next paragraph would have been kind of up in here.

00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:31.680
 And then maybe it would have wrapped if it was long enough.

00:03:31.680 --> 00:03:35.560
 And when you play with this, you can resize it and see how the wrapping changes.

00:03:35.560 --> 00:03:39.240
 But no matter what the size is, after the br clear equals all,

00:03:39.240 --> 00:03:43.880
 this is gonna format back to the left nav, right?

00:03:43.880 --> 00:03:47.720
 So that clears that hanging wrap, that sort of, but you don't have to.

00:03:47.720 --> 00:03:50.800
 You could not do this, and then it would wrap and wrap and wrap, and

00:03:50.800 --> 00:03:52.400
 then it would get longer, and it would continue on.

00:03:52.400 --> 00:03:56.560
 But if you want control over that, you can with the br clear equals all.

00:03:56.560 --> 00:04:01.080
 And of course, you can have images right in line.

00:04:01.080 --> 00:04:04.240
 And this is just from the HTML bit here.

00:04:04.240 --> 00:04:05.720
 There's nothing fancy CSS here.

00:04:05.720 --> 00:04:08.360
 Images kind of are like big characters.

00:04:08.360 --> 00:04:10.520
 I sized that one so it sort of fit nicely, and

00:04:10.520 --> 00:04:12.360
 you can even make this a clickable link.

00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:16.600
 But that's really just this part here is just HTML, not CSS.

00:04:16.600 --> 00:04:21.560
 But I could have if I wanted to change the width and the height of this.

00:04:21.560 --> 00:04:24.980
 That'd be kind of fun, make this guy be like the width of an M, and

00:04:24.980 --> 00:04:26.760
 then you'd see it more like a character.

00:04:26.760 --> 00:04:30.080
 So there's a bunch of colors.

00:04:30.080 --> 00:04:37.240
 And the colors have to do with the simple thing for us simple folks.

00:04:37.240 --> 00:04:40.400
 We just put in things like red and green and stuff like that.

00:04:40.400 --> 00:04:43.520
 And especially if you're doing a developer and you're just trying to

00:04:43.520 --> 00:04:44.800
 get basic stuff working.

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:48.720
 I often use colors in my testing that like put the border red.

00:04:48.720 --> 00:04:51.840
 I do that all the time to say, where was that div at anyway?

00:04:51.840 --> 00:04:56.280
 So I'll throw a one pixel border around it, red border, like that's where it is.

00:04:56.280 --> 00:05:00.120
 Although the Chris Pedrick plugin has a thing where it puts one pixel borders

00:05:00.120 --> 00:05:02.320
 around everything for you automatically, but whatever.

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:05.800
 These are not necessarily most graphically beautiful colors,

00:05:05.800 --> 00:05:09.080
 even though I like them cuz they're super primary in terms of primary colors and

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:13.680
 strong, and you'll see that I kinda use those colors in my slides a lot.

00:05:13.680 --> 00:05:15.840
 Because I'm not a graphic artist, of course.

00:05:15.840 --> 00:05:18.600
 I just like, the greenest I can be is good.

00:05:18.600 --> 00:05:22.260
 So there's 16 official colors, and they're here.

00:05:22.260 --> 00:05:30.200
 Once you get a little more sophisticated, you can use precise colors from,

00:05:30.200 --> 00:05:35.520
 I think this is a 32 bit, yeah.

00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:40.340
 So this precise colors are the ones that start with pound sign, and so

00:05:40.340 --> 00:05:43.280
 pound sign, and these are hexadecimal numbers.

00:05:43.280 --> 00:05:48.080
 These two numbers are effectively 0 through 255, but they're in hex.

00:05:48.080 --> 00:05:54.400
 So hexes like A, B, C, D, E, F are actually numbers, 0 through 9.

00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:58.620
 This is actually 10, 11, 12, 13, this is 15.

00:05:58.620 --> 00:06:03.440
 And so E is bigger than 9, and F is bigger than E.

00:06:03.440 --> 00:06:08.560
 But basically these are 0 through 256, that's a three top of those 0 through 256

00:06:08.560 --> 00:06:09.520
 numbers.

00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:11.880
 And so the more red you put in, the higher this is.

00:06:11.880 --> 00:06:14.040
 The more green you put in, the higher that is.

00:06:14.040 --> 00:06:18.720
 And the more blue you put in, the higher that is, so RGB, red, green, blue.

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:21.440
 And if you're playing with like a slider inside your UI,

00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:25.480
 you might be changing this, but you're just changing these numbers ultimately.

00:06:25.480 --> 00:06:28.600
 And so you can find these things.

00:06:30.600 --> 00:06:37.560
 So white is all Fs, and so if you turn it all on, it's white.

00:06:37.560 --> 00:06:42.960
 If you turn it all off, it's black, the absence color is black, red, green.

00:06:42.960 --> 00:06:47.680
 So that's max, max, and max, and so you can make sort of a pure red,

00:06:47.680 --> 00:06:48.880
 pure green, and pure blue.

00:06:48.880 --> 00:06:52.840
 Picking these advanced colors is sort of way beyond my ability as a graphic artist,

00:06:52.840 --> 00:06:54.400
 and people will pick colors.

00:06:54.400 --> 00:06:59.720
 There are sites that help you pick palettes for your pages, etc, etc, etc.

00:06:59.720 --> 00:07:05.240
 There is also a, sometimes these colors can have a transparency and

00:07:05.240 --> 00:07:09.680
 there's a fourth set of two numbers that have to do with how transparent the color

00:07:09.680 --> 00:07:10.200
 might be.

00:07:10.200 --> 00:07:14.040
 So fonts are also important.

00:07:14.040 --> 00:07:20.080
 The default font is a Times Roman because that's what computers had in 1994.

00:07:20.080 --> 00:07:23.120
 And I think they're ugly, especially on screens.

00:07:23.120 --> 00:07:26.480
 They're not so bad on print, but they're ugly on screens.

00:07:26.480 --> 00:07:31.080
 And so I tend to want a sans-serif font, it's too bad that they, and

00:07:31.080 --> 00:07:34.200
 maybe they have changed in some browser default for sans-serif.

00:07:34.200 --> 00:07:37.160
 I just change it to sans-serif all the time I want.

00:07:37.160 --> 00:07:42.720
 Now if you look at fonts, the font family is kind of a special tag in that

00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:45.520
 you ask it a set of fonts.

00:07:45.520 --> 00:07:48.360
 And what you're really doing is you're setting a priority.

00:07:48.360 --> 00:07:51.400
 And the problem is, is depending on whether you're on Windows or Mac, or

00:07:51.400 --> 00:07:54.960
 which version of Windows, or which browser, or what fonts they've had installed,

00:07:56.320 --> 00:07:59.320
 you can, fonts might not be there.

00:07:59.320 --> 00:08:03.000
 And so what you basically do is you basically say, okay, I would like this.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:04.960
 I think this is a Microsoft font.

00:08:04.960 --> 00:08:07.300
 And if that font's not there, then I would like this font.

00:08:07.300 --> 00:08:10.240
 And I think that might be also a Microsoft font.

00:08:10.240 --> 00:08:12.400
 And if that font's not there, then there's Arial.

00:08:12.400 --> 00:08:13.880
 See how much I know about graphic arts?

00:08:13.880 --> 00:08:14.640
 I have no idea.

00:08:14.640 --> 00:08:16.440
 I think this might be a Mac font.

00:08:16.440 --> 00:08:21.240
 And if that font doesn't work, default into the fallback font sans-serif.

00:08:21.240 --> 00:08:25.280
 And there is always going to be a serif font, Times New Roman-like, sans-serif,

00:08:25.280 --> 00:08:29.300
 Arial-like, Monospace, which is Courier-like, Curse of Infantasy,

00:08:29.300 --> 00:08:31.080
 which are whatever.

00:08:31.080 --> 00:08:35.780
 And so all browsers are supposed to have those fallback fonts.

00:08:35.780 --> 00:08:38.280
 And so you tend to see them here at the very end.

00:08:38.280 --> 00:08:41.560
 And so when you see me, I usually will say Arial sans-serif or

00:08:41.560 --> 00:08:43.720
 something like that, just to get sans-serif.

00:08:43.720 --> 00:08:47.960
 Although it's quite common, the more sophisticated a page is, the more likely.

00:08:47.960 --> 00:08:52.320
 And the other thing that's increasingly the case is people are downloading fonts

00:08:52.320 --> 00:08:55.240
 and having special, beautiful web fonts.

00:08:55.240 --> 00:08:58.040
 And then they download them and then they put that font in here, but

00:08:58.040 --> 00:08:59.600
 then they probably still have fallback fonts.

00:08:59.600 --> 00:09:04.280
 So font family is kind of a weird and unique and

00:09:04.280 --> 00:09:07.480
 glorious thing that leads to some really gorgeous web pages.

00:09:07.480 --> 00:09:12.240
 Cuz so much graphic arts work is going into making wedge pages beautiful.

00:09:12.240 --> 00:09:15.520
 And we're going way beyond the operating system installed fonts and

00:09:15.520 --> 00:09:17.480
 having pages that download their own fonts.

00:09:18.720 --> 00:09:23.040
 Things that you can do is set the things to bold, italic, text decoration.

00:09:23.040 --> 00:09:27.080
 Remember, links have underlines and we can turn them on or off.

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:35.040
 Font sizes are kind of troublesome in that you can set them to pixels.

00:09:35.040 --> 00:09:38.800
 But then you're in danger if you get to a certain kind of a screen size or

00:09:38.800 --> 00:09:41.040
 people start zooming the screen and stuff.

00:09:41.040 --> 00:09:44.040
 And so you can tend to use these relative ones, but

00:09:44.040 --> 00:09:48.760
 they're not as guaranteed as you might like them to be.

00:09:48.760 --> 00:09:53.360
 And so just these are a little bit tricky.

00:09:53.360 --> 00:09:56.640
 Absolute font sizes are a little bit dangerous.

00:09:56.640 --> 00:10:01.480
 I tend to just go like, here's my font, here's the one that's a little larger,

00:10:01.480 --> 00:10:03.200
 here's a little smaller, if I need that.

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:08.200
 So most of the time I'm tending to do things that are smaller.

00:10:08.200 --> 00:10:09.920
 If I'm putting a copyright statement and

00:10:09.920 --> 00:10:13.960
 I don't wanna distract from the main page, I'll just make it a little small.

00:10:13.960 --> 00:10:17.960
 I'll say, okay, make this small or extra small.

00:10:17.960 --> 00:10:21.120
 And what if it doesn't turn out to be that much smaller?

00:10:21.120 --> 00:10:22.040
 It doesn't matter.

00:10:22.040 --> 00:10:27.000
 I'm just kinda trying to, so I'm not an expert in how to use those.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:29.200
 I tend to use them as simply as I possibly can,

00:10:29.200 --> 00:10:31.560
 cuz they're not as predictable as it would be nice if they were.

00:10:31.560 --> 00:10:35.720
 So links were in a big part of the early web.

00:10:35.720 --> 00:10:40.200
 And it's called hypertext markup language, hypertext transport layer,

00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:42.080
 hypertext, hypertext, hypertext.

00:10:42.080 --> 00:10:44.400
 And so links got really special treatment.

00:10:44.400 --> 00:10:48.760
 They used to be blue before you clicked on them and

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:50.680
 purple after you clicked on them.

00:10:50.680 --> 00:10:53.200
 The blue was to jump out at you and say, please click me.

00:10:53.200 --> 00:10:57.600
 And the purple was to say, I've been there, because a lot of what you did in

00:10:57.600 --> 00:11:01.160
 the early web is you wandered from place to place to place to place is like,

00:11:01.160 --> 00:11:03.280
 I found a new thing, let me explore this.

00:11:03.280 --> 00:11:05.640
 And so you're always exploring by clicking links.

00:11:05.640 --> 00:11:08.040
 Once we got to the point where people assumed the web,

00:11:08.040 --> 00:11:12.260
 these links didn't need to be blue and garish colors to teach us these things,

00:11:12.260 --> 00:11:14.440
 cuz people just clicked on everything.

00:11:14.440 --> 00:11:17.280
 And so it became more important to make things pretty.

00:11:17.280 --> 00:11:20.640
 So we have a lot of control as to how we style links.

00:11:20.640 --> 00:11:27.500
 We can say the A tag, we've already colored an A tag with just the A at the top.

00:11:27.500 --> 00:11:31.600
 You can basically say an unvisited link is supposed to have the color black.

00:11:31.600 --> 00:11:33.840
 After the visit, it's supposed to be gray.

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:37.160
 While you're hovering over top of it, it's supposed to have text decoration and

00:11:37.160 --> 00:11:40.480
 none of them being black, white with a background of navy.

00:11:40.480 --> 00:11:42.600
 And then active is not so heavily used.

00:11:42.600 --> 00:11:45.720
 It's once you've clicked on the link while the page is loaded.

00:11:45.720 --> 00:11:49.720
 So it's a way to kinda maybe disable it or turn it to color so

00:11:49.720 --> 00:11:52.880
 people think, I better wait until this next page loads.

00:11:52.880 --> 00:11:54.680
 And so when I do the recording, you'll see this.

00:11:54.680 --> 00:11:57.560
 It's a lot easier to see this dynamically.

00:11:57.560 --> 00:12:00.320
 And so there's a whole bunch more samples that I have.

00:12:00.320 --> 00:12:03.240
 And I'll record some walkthroughs of every single one of the samples.

00:12:03.240 --> 00:12:06.240
 And so you can take a look at that at web applications for

00:12:06.240 --> 00:12:07.920
 everybody or in the recordings.

00:12:07.920 --> 00:12:13.080
 So this has been a zoom through CSS.

00:12:13.080 --> 00:12:16.160
 CSS is quite the art and science and it's evolutionary.

00:12:16.160 --> 00:12:17.800
 I mean, people specialize in this.

00:12:17.800 --> 00:12:18.840
 They're very good at it.

00:12:18.840 --> 00:12:21.120
 It's a modern form of graphic arts.

00:12:21.120 --> 00:12:24.240
 The basics are there, and I think every programmer who does anything on the web

00:12:24.240 --> 00:12:27.240
 should know the basics of HTML.

00:12:27.240 --> 00:12:34.240
 They keep moving things better with things like nav tags and bootstrap, etc.

00:12:34.240 --> 00:12:39.100
 And while there will always be edgy new things in CSS, and so

00:12:39.100 --> 00:12:43.840
 sometimes you'll see CSS with these Moz fields, which are from Mozilla for

00:12:43.840 --> 00:12:47.080
 the Firefox, but people are always pushing that boundary.

00:12:47.080 --> 00:12:50.080
 And before you couldn't put rounded corners on things, but

00:12:50.080 --> 00:12:53.720
 then the browsers added extensions to put rounded corners on things.

00:12:53.720 --> 00:12:55.480
 And then everybody kind of agreed on that.

00:12:55.480 --> 00:12:59.360
 So CSS is kind of always gonna get better and better and better because for

00:12:59.360 --> 00:13:03.880
 the mobile and desktop, they really wanna create as beautiful experiences

00:13:03.880 --> 00:13:06.600
 as possible and use standards wherever possible.

00:13:06.600 --> 00:13:09.400
 And so the basics are there.

00:13:09.400 --> 00:13:13.160
 You can do so many wonderful things, especially if you pull in something like

00:13:13.160 --> 00:13:17.760
 a bootstrap that just kind of cleans up the rough edges of HTML and

00:13:17.760 --> 00:13:21.960
 makes it generally pretty and takes a lot of responsibility off of you.

00:13:21.960 --> 00:13:26.880
 But you can certainly make a lifetime study of CSS if you like.

00:13:26.880 --> 00:13:28.480
 So I hope you found this useful.

00:13:28.480 --> 00:13:29.600
 I will see you on the net.

